<TEXT>
gov gaston caperton made some progress 
with union officials monday in a bid to end west virginias first 
teacher strike a spokesman said 
earlier in the day about 1000 teachers and their supporters 
rallied at the capitol and one county threatened to fire teachers 
who dont return to work 
caperton met with kayetta meadows president of the 
16000member west virginia education association and bob brown 
president of the 3000member west virginia federation of teachers 
behind closed doors for about seven hours the meeting ended at 11 
pm 
caperton spokesman gc morse said no agreement had been reached 
to end the strike but the two sides were closer to a settlement 
than they have been in the past few days 
morse declined to elaborate on the talks he said discussions 
would resume at 7 am tuesday brown would not comment after the 
meeting and meadows said only that she was tired but willing to 
continue talks 
it is my hope and desire that we can put aside the harsh words 
and miscommunications of the past weekend and move on to the 
resolution of the present predicament caperton said in a news 
release issued before the meeting i hope that this discussion 
will be framed in realistic and practical terms 
as the meeting continued inside the capitol hundreds of 
teachers clad in red as a sign of solidarity gathered outside under 
a huge banner reading governor lead us dont fight us 
this isnt fun but it is necessary said keith geiger 
president of the 2 millionmember national education association 
with which the wvea is affiliated you must stick together until 
a resolution is there 
teachers went on strike last wednesday after the governor failed 
to provide educators with a raise in his 199091 proposed budget 
by monday the strike had spread to 46 of the states 55 
counties forcing officials in 29 counties to cancel classes for 
nearly 150000 of the states 328445 pupils 
the meeting came after talks between the two sides broke down 
over the weekend 
leaders of the education association said they had been ready to 
call off the walkout saturday but urged members to remain on 
strike accusing the governor of reneging on the terms of a 
settlement 
the teachers said they wont go back to work until the governor 
promises to call a special legislative session to consider pay 
raises the governor said he wont call a special session until the 
teachers go back to work 
assocation members voted saturday on a proposal to return to 
work for 30 days during which time caperton would call a special 
session 
but caperton termed a total lie any claim that he promised 
to call such a session meadows said the governor gave teachers no 
choice but to stay on strike 
in greenbrier county in the southeastern section of the state 
the board of education told striking teachers monday they would be 
fired if they didnt return to work by wednesday 
state attorney general roger tompkins said last week the 
teachers strike is illegal and teachers could be fired or otherwise 
disciplined 
in jefferson county in the northeast circuit judge thomas 
steptoe issued an injunction ordering county teachers to return to 
classrooms by thursday 
the county board of education asked for the injunction after 
teachers there voted to go on strike last thursday steptoe said 
teachers could be fined and held in contempt of court if they 
didnt return by the deadline 
carolyn spangler a spokeswoman for the state board of 
education said she knew of no similar action at county or state 
levels 
in ohio county in the northern panhandle classes were canceled 
when officials found most of the districts 47 school buses had 
flat tires said superintendent h lawrence jones jones said it 
was unclear who was responsible 
in classrooms and on picket lines teachers blasted caperton and 
the news media saying a failure to communicate has been a major 
problem in settling the strike 
at charlestons capitol high school only about 400 of the 
schools 1300 students showed up for classes 
i dont like it because weve been wasting our time said 
shawna adkins a sophomore at capitol all we do is watch movies 
and we can do that at home 
</TEXT>
