<TEXT>
the five permanent members of the un security 
council met privately monday in their third round of discussions 
since january on a formula to end the 11yearold cambodian civil 
war 
the diplomats from france the united states soviet union 
china and britain were expected to focus on the failure of a 
meeting of the four warring factions two weeks ago 
in january the five security council members supported large 
parts of an australian plan to put cambodia under un 
administration until free elections were held they met again in 
new york last month 
analysts believe the australian plan offers the best chance in 
years of ending the conflict but the meeting of the combatants in 
jakarta indonesia produced no agreement on major issues 
factions involved are the government of premier hun sen 
installed by vietnam and the resistance coalition of three parties 
the khmer rouge a communist group that is the strongest 
guerrilla organization and noncommunist insurgent forces led by 
prince norodom sihanouk cambodias former ruler and son sann a 
former premier 
hun sen and vietnams foreign minister nguyen co thach said 
one reason the jakarta talks failed was the opposition of khieu 
samphan a khmer rouge leader and vice president of the guerrilla 
coalition to using the word genocide to describe khmer rouge 
rule of cambodia in 197578 
the khmer rouge government led by pol pot killed hundreds of 
thousands of cambodias 8 million people in the process of trying 
to create a new agrarian society a vietnamese invasion in december 
1978 overthrew the pol pot regime 
australias plan also is intended to break a deadlock at the 
19nation paris talks in august which foundered largely on the 
question of how power could be shared until election the 
australians suggested sidestepping the question by putting the 
country under an interim un administration with peacekeeping 
forces to police a ceasefire 
all factions appear to accept some un role including election 
supervision but there is disagreement over how cambodia should be 
governed until the elections are held 
hun sen and his vietnamese backers say dismantling his 
government might open the way for the khmer rouge to seize power 
again 
sihanouk and son sann have welcomed the australian proposal 
khmer rouge spokesmen have expressed reservations about it but 
have not taken a formal position 
under the australian plan the former french colonys un seat 
would be declared vacant until a new government was formed in phnom 
penh after elections the plan would cost an estimated 987 million 
for a year and involve 12190 peacekeepers and outside officials 
attending the paris talks are richard solomon us 
undersecretary of state david gillmore undersecretary in the 
british foreign office claude martin frances director of asian 
affairs igor rogachev of the soviet union and xu dunxin of china 
vice ministers of foreign affairs and rafeeuden ahmed a un 
assistant secretarygeneral 
</TEXT>
