<TEXT>
former cia director francis raborn jr who 
led development of the polaris missile as a navy officer has died 
of cardiac arrest at 84 
raborn a retired navy vice admiral was appointed by president 
johnson to head the central intelligence agency in 1965 he was 
succeed by richard helms his deputy the following year 
an aviator raborn served aboard aircraft carriers in world war 
ii and commanded the carrier bennington after the war 
in 1955 he was chosen to head navy missile development and 
brought in the nucleartipped polaris missile on time and on 
budget it was the first solidfuel longrange missile launchable 
from a submerged submarine 
raborn died march 6 at sibley hospital according to obituaries 
published tuesday 
he is survived by his wife two children and four grandchildren 
 
