<TEXT>
deposed haitian leader prosper avril stopped at a 
us air force base monday before flying to an unknown destination 
as haitian exiles cautiously celebrated his ouster and called for 
his execution 
avril a lieutenant general and his family arrived aboard a 
us c141 transport plane at homestead air force base 25 miles 
south of miami at 820 am and left at 330 pm 
avril departed in personally arranged transportation said 
maj bob barca a homestead spokesman he declined to comment 
further 
a us government official speaking on condition he not be 
identified said avril left florida asked if he was flown out the 
official responded that would be correct 
lt col darrell hayes an air force spokesman in washington 
said earlier that avril was going to be driven to boca raton and 
left on his own after reaching the affluent palm beach county 
city but city officials said they were assured by federal 
officials that avril wasnt coming there 
area haitians said avrils son attended college in miami until 
recently and moved to a home west of boca raton the sunsentinel 
in fort lauderdale reported tuesday 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said earlier that avril 
indicated he planned to stay in the miami area a few days and 
that his future was still under discussion 
a group of haitian exiles demonstrated briefly outside the us 
attorneys office in miami to call for avrils indictment dozens 
more gathered outside the haitian refugee center in miamis little 
haiti neighborhood listening to radio reporters and speakers 
avril pa mourin avril isnt dead some chanted in haitian 
creole the frenchafrican language spoken by most haitians most 
speakers called for avrils capture trial in haiti and execution 
for allegedly ordering the slayings of civilians and opposition 
leaders 
the crowd became larger and livelier as nightfall neared but 
the overall mood seemed more anxious than boisterous after four 
years of instability and dashed hopes in their caribbean homeland 
the mood contrasted with nearriotous celebrations that broke out 
on feb 7 1986 when jeanclaude baby doc duvalier fled haiti 
ending his familys 29year rule 
everybody is happy but we are still watching said pierre 
joseph 30 who said hes been in florida 10 years nothing 
changed yet maybe if we have elections then it will change 
a dozen haitians stood vigil outside the homestead base gates 
when word began circulating that avril was on his way 
were here to tell him hes not welcome in this society in 
this country said exile jeanpierre louis we want him to be 
tried and imprisoned and even executed like ceaucescu in romania 
louis said us hospitality for avril was unwelcome but the 
rev gerard jeanjuste a longtime fiery leader in the south 
florida exile community that numbers at least 150000 urged cool 
heads 
leading the demonstration outside the us attorneys office he 
said avril should be indicted and jailed on drug charges as was 
deposed panama leader gen manuel antonio noriega in federal 
custody near here since his own arrival at homestead on jan 4 
the haitian military has been linked to shipments of south 
american cocaine to florida but there has been no indication that 
us authorities might charge avril 
as far as any charges are concerned this office will attempt 
to bring an indictment if there is sufficient evidence and 
information to justify it said diane cossin executive assistant 
to us attorney dexter lehtinen she suggested anyone with such 
information turn it over to the drug enforcement administration 
jeanjuste twice this year led demonstrations at miami 
international airport when avril was in transit during an official 
visit to taiwan the exiles there were ordered by police to 
disperse after threatening to grab avril and take him to little 
haiti for a peoples trial 
i am very optimistic this time i think there are new factors 
in the equation jeanjuste said 
he said he was most encouraged by the apparent role the us 
ambassador state department and white house played in easing avril 
out many haitian exiles have expressed bitterness about us 
policy toward haiti and haitian immigration which is to consider 
most haitians attempting to leave their impoverished nation to be 
economic refugees and subject to deportation 
this is a miracle for us to see many of the us officials 
helping get the rights of the haitian people jeanjuste said 
he said haitians were trying to learn more about ertha 
pascaltrouillot the supreme court judge designated by the 
opposition coalition to head a provisional civilian government 
she had ties to the duvalier regime jeanjuste said but added 
if the haitian people accept her we will accept her we will be 
very cautious 
he doubted there would be a mass reverse exodus to haiti if 
democracy comes he said haiti doesnt have the infrastructure to 
support a surge of returning exiles most of whom send us dollars 
home jeanjuste said he would encourage exiles to go back 
temporarily to help and to take goods not available in haiti 
