<TEXT>
was joseph hazelwood drunk or sober 
when the exxon valdez ran aground a defense witness said a 
toxicologist for the prosecution probably cant tell because 
there are too many unknown variables 
thomas burr an alcohol and drug testing consultant from 
minneapolis noted monday that hazelwood underwent only one blood 
test 10 hours after the grounding and it is not known whether he 
drank after the grounding 
burr called by the defense criticized conclusions reached by 
richard prouty an oklahoma toxicologist who testified hazelwood 
probably was drunk when his tanker rammed a jagged reef in the 
nations worst oil spill 
prouty used a method known as retrograde extrapolation 
which seeks to determine a persons drunkenness at an earlier hour 
through backward calculations based on blood tests 
but burr said hes never heard of anyone counting backwards 10 
hours with only one blood test 
its very dubious when its based on a single chemical test 
he said in my opinion its not a valid thing to do forensically 
especially not for such a long period of time there are too 
many unknown variables 
burr said the method is controversial in the scientific 
community 
taking proutys calculations to their extreme burr said they 
could have shown that hazelwood had a 30 blood alcohol reading 
when he boarded the ship making him unable to walk straight 
at levels of 30 100 percent of people are visibly and 
noticeably intoxicated burr said he faced crossexamination 
today 
witnesses have said hazelwood was steady on his feet and except 
for liquor on his breath showed no signs of intoxication after a 
day ashore in valdez there is a conflict in testimony on how much 
he drank while in town 
earlier monday another defense expert witness shiras walker 
testified under crossexamination that the grounding of the massive 
tanker would not have occurred if hazelwood had stayed on the 
bridge 
but walker a former tanker captain said the skippers 
departure to his quarters was not unusual and did not cause the 
disaster walker said if he had things to do below and had an able 
third mate he wouldnt hesitate to leave either 
i walked several thousand miles in captain hazelwoods 
shoes the experienced seaman said 
ultimately walker blamed third mate gregory cousins for the 
wreck he suggested it was cousins job to see that hazelwoods 
orders were followed by the helmsman who failed to carry out the 
ordered 10degree right rudder turn 
probably anybody above the age of 5 could have carried that 
out the witness said 
if there were problems walker said the third mate had a 
telephone to call hazelwood in his cabin all he had to say was 
captain come to the bridge and this whole thing would have been 
avoided he testified 
hazelwood 43 of huntington ny was the only crew member of 
the exxon valdez charged in the wreck which spilled nearly 11 
million gallons of oil 
he is accused of criminal mischief reckless endangerment 
operating a vessel while intoxicated and negligent discharge of 
oil if convicted he could receive up to 7 years in prison and 
61000 in fines 
isnt it true that if captain hazelwood was on the bridge 
where he was supposed to be this wouldnt have happened 
assistant district attorney mary anne henry asked during 
crossexamination 
i might disagree with that supposed to be part said 
walker but if captain hazelwood was on the bridge during those 
maneuvers this accident wouldnt have happened 
but when defense attorney michael chalos asked whether he felt 
hazelwoods absence from the bridge contributed to the disaster in 
any way the witness responded none at all 
the former captain told jurors the only regulation he knows of 
requiring a captain to be on the bridge is during passage through 
the panama canal 
</TEXT>
