<TEXT>
a year ago islamic fundamentalist ahmed 
kofahi had been dismissed as a university teacher and was in prison 
for criticizing the government now hes a member of parliament 
kofahi is heard regularly in state radio broadcasts of 
parliamentary debates excoriating assorted government officials 
his progress from prisoner to legislator illustrates the quiet 
changes jordan has undergone the past year 
the atmospheres different now kofahi said in an interview 
we have more freedom but its not enough 
islamic fundamentalists and leftists who won seats in the 
november elections are pressing for tough investigations of 
government corruption greater social justice and curbs on security 
agencies 
human rights are born before the human is born kofahi said 
its not a gift from a leader or a party or an authority and not 
to have these rights is equivalent to death 
jordan is bordered to the north and east by syria and iraq 
whose ruling parties brook little opposition kuwait the most 
liberal state on the arabian peninsula to the south suspended its 
parliament in 1987 
im sure the countries surrounding us are not happy about 
whats going on here said taher masri who resigned from the 
cabinet to make a successful run for parliament 
reform in this kingdom of 31 million people whose western 
neighbor is israel is more orderly and less sweeping than the 
change revolutionizing eastern europe 
as in eastern europe however popular revolt is behind it four 
days of riots last april caused by price increases and other 
grievances cost 10 lives and shocked king hussein into action 
hussein who has ruled since 1953 is relinquishing many powers 
but retains firm control and is personally popular 
in november he oversaw jordans first general elections since 
1967 which were among the freest ever held in the arab world 
the fundamentalist moslem brotherhood won the largest bloc of 
seats in the 80member parliament kofahi running on the 
brotherhood ticket got more votes than any of the other 650 
candidates 
mudar badran husseins choice for prime minister underwent an 
extraordinary grilling by legislators about his personal finances 
and professional record before winning a vote of confidence 
since last april the government has freed all prisoners held 
without charge and dozens convicted of political related crimes 
radicals who once took up arms against hussein have been allowed 
to return home and the pervasive general intelligence department 
has been stripped of its powers to withhold passports and bar 
people from travel or employment 
the government has promised to make officials accountable for 
corruption a former undersecretary of the supply ministry was 
arrested last month in a graft investigation 
badran has promised to end martial law imposed 23 years ago 
because of the 1967 middle east war and appointed lawyers to 
determine which of the decrees issued during that time should be 
abolished 
he also promised to repeal a 1935 defense law inherited from the 
british mandate that allows officials to ignore many civil rights 
the law now is used more widely in israel than in jordan 
although the 33yearold ban on political parties remains in 
force it was ignored during the election campaign the government 
says it will legalize parties after a new national charter of 
principles is submitted to a referendum probably this year 
police have not interfered with street demonstrations which 
have been few and small a 1988 decree nationalizing newspapers was 
canceled and they were returned to their former managers but 
government institutions retain majority ownership 
the government is not involved in any way in restricting the 
press information minister ibrahim izzeddine said 
all the changes have not been liberal the victory of islamic 
fundamentalists set back campaigns for westernstyle womens rights 
and encouraged censorship on moral grounds 
masri the former government minister said he is convinced 
hussein will not retreat from reforms 
jordan has had parliaments since the 1920s most were weak and 
any that showed signs of independence were suspended 
since 1948 however jordan has gone from a land of peasants and 
nomads with one high school to a nation that nearly equals sweden 
in the percentage of young people going to college or technical 
school 
with such an educated population masri said you cant hide 
anything anymore 
