<TEXT>
brad waller teaches shakespearean sword 
fighters how to take the ouch out of touche 
a certified expert in stage combat waller can turn an amateur 
swashbuckler into a douglas fairbanks or errol flynn in 15 weeks of 
strenuous monday night sessions at washingtons folger shakespeare 
theater 
for a 350 fee waller trains actors in the art of dueling with 
such deadly weapons as rapier and dagger broadsword and 
quarterstaff without committing mayhem on the stage but 
convincing theatergoers theyre seeing the real thing 
his rapiers slashing attacks stop perilously close to a 
students arms legs or abdomen before each parry and thrust he 
gives broad visual clues to make his next move as obvious as 
possible his bucklers the shield between a swords blade and 
handle are fashioned from hubcaps and silverplated candy dishes 
wallers deft movements are patterned after the highly refined 
techniques of camillo agrippa achille marozzo and other 16th 
century fencing masters whose books he has studied in the archives 
of the folger shakespeare library 
those techniques can be very dangerous waller said in a 
way they were meant to kill so stage combat can never be 
historically accurate or youd kill the actors i try to teach 
safety first and the skills to make the actor really look good 
the ebullient redhaired waller 34 a wisconsinborn actor who 
grew up in minneapolis learned his craft under paddy crean dean 
of the society of american fight directors it was crean who taught 
errol flynn how to handle his rapier with wit 
paddy always said that stage combat is 75 percent drama 15 
percent historical accuracy and 100 percent safety said waller 
one of only five students to receive the societys demanding 
teaching certificate in 1988 
boxoffice stars who have been coached by society professionals 
in fight choreography which includes fisticuffs as well as 
swordplay include christopher walken william hurt jon voigt 
henry winkler kathleen turner and amy irving 
when hes not working with actors teaching in local schools or 
performing onstage waller hits the road with shakespeare 
lunatics and lovers an elizabethan theatrical troupe that stages 
battles and love scenes from the bard of avons plays before high 
school audiences 
people no longer settle feuds in a fencing duel but waller says 
there will be a big demand for classical actors trained in 
swordplay as long as shakespeares plays are performed 
shakespeares works are full of bloody sword fights and 
suicides in keeping with the elizabethan tradition of pleasing 
audiences not only with plays but competitive bouts of swordplay 
waller said some of shakespeares stage roles including clowns 
and fools were written for fencing masters of the day 
in romeo and juliet the hotheaded tybalt who tilts with 
piercing steel at bold mercutios breast took his name from 
girard thibault who wrote a manual in 1628 describing the quick 
precise cutting motions of the spanish style of fencing 
before he was slain at tybalts hand mercutio called his 
adversary the very butcher of a silk button waller said that 
referred to an italian fencing master in london probably known to 
shakespeare who could take the silk buttons off any englishman 
with his rapier 
the english language in fact is rich with words and phrases 
that originated in fencing waller said 
when you say you crossed someone or gave him the slip you are 
using old fencing terms for maneuvers designed to thwart an 
opponent he said if you say come to the point you are 
really challenging someone to a duel 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

