<TEXT>
stripped of recognition by the us government 
in 1897 the miami indian tribe has pinned its hopes of prosperity 
on regaining its identity 
federal recognition could translate into millions in economic 
aid and social services while helping to preserve the identity of 
the 6000member tribe based for centuries in the flat woodlands 
of northern indiana 
since 1980 the tribe has submitted 10 volumes of documentation 
including the names of each tribe member proof of the tribes 
longstanding existence includes the indiana towns named after 
chiefs muncie and kokomo 
the bureau of indian affairs has promised to try to decide on 
recognition by friday although officials said the decision could 
be delayed 
i dont see how it could go against us because the miamis are 
probably the best documented tribe east of the mississippi 
tribal chairman raymond white said last week the word out in 
indian country and washington is that if the miamis dont make it 
there wont be another tribe that will make it 
under guidelines set up in 1978 landless tribes can gain access 
to federal aid and other advantages once they gain official 
recognition 
the recognition process has proved to be a bureaucratic 
nightmare for the more than 100 tribes that have applied mostly 
small tribes from the east and west coasts seven have been 
acknowledged and 12 denied said bia spokesman carl shaw 
recognition would allow the miami nation to set tax rates for 
its businesses sell taxfree municipal bonds and become eligible 
for programs administered by the bia and the indian health service 
white who runs the tribe on behalf of its ailing 75yearold 
chief francisco shoemaker has ambitious plans for the miamis 
under his guidance the tribe in december started a joint 
venture with medimail inc a san diego calif drug distributor 
the tribe finds customers among indian clinics and hospitals around 
the country for medimail 
recognition could open the door to a federal loan to expand the 
tribes pharmacy business the tribe also has plans for a 50unit 
federally funded housing complex and a health clinic in peru 
the drug warehouse and other projects would create about 100 
jobs for the miamis about 2000 of whom are scattered among eight 
northern indiana counties white said the tribe has no land of its 
own 
