<TEXT>
the bush administration today expressed 
support anew for lithuanias move toward independence but said it 
will delay formal recognition of the breakaway republic until the 
lithuanians are in control of their own destiny 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater reiterated the 
administrations call upon the soviet central government to 
respect the will of the citizens of the baltic state 
but the administration stopped short of recognizing the 
government formed by a unanimous vote sunday of the new lithuanian 
parliament in vilnius 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev opening a congress of 
communist party deputies today in moscow called lithuanias 
declaration of independence alarming but gave no indication he 
plans any action to prevent the baltic republic from seceding 
gorbachev has said previously that lithuania would have to pay 
the kremlin 34 billion for the factories and other infrastructure 
built during a halfcentury of soviet rule lithuanians say they 
are owed even more for decades of soviet repression including 
mass deportations to siberia under stalin 
fitzwater asked at a briefing why the united states did not 
immediately recognize the new lithuanian government said 
because we would want any recognition to take into account a 
final government that was in control of their own destiny and much 
of that has yet to be negotiated with the soviet union 
he emphasized the united states has never recognized the soviet 
unions forcible annexation in 1940 of lithuania and its two sister 
baltic republics estonia and latvia he said the united states 
wants to foster productive negotiations 
we believe this is the right measure of support fitzwater 
said it reflects our policy of many years of not recognizing 
their incorporation in the first place it reflects the fact that 
they still have negotiations to carry out that we want to be 
successful 
the white house in a statement sunday by fitzwater urged 
gorbachev to enter immediate constructive negotiations with the 
lithuanians and said we have consistently supported the baltic 
peoples inalienable right to peaceful selfdetermination 
it urged the soviet government to respect the will of the 
citizens of lithuania as expressed through their freely elected 
representatives 
the united states also expects the government of lithuania to 
consider the rights of its minority population he said 
we hope that all parties will continue to avoid any initiation 
or encouragement of violence fitzwater said 
a lithuanian diplomat in washington said western governments are 
likely to wait to recognize lithuanias declaration of independence 
