<TEXT>
writer and poet philippe soupault one of the 
founders of the surrealist movement has died at the age of 92 
soupault died sunday night in his paris home no cause of death 
was announced 
the magnetic fields a poem soupault wrote with andre 
breton was first published in 1919 and is considered the work that 
gave birth to the surrealist movement 
born in the exclusive paris suburb of chaville and educated at 
the sorbonne soupault was influenced by the works of marcel proust 
and his voyages to germany and england 
but the horrors of world war i proved a stronger influence and 
in march 1919 he joined breton and louis aragon to found the review 
literature 
the magazine quickly became the standardbearer for 
intellectuals disillusioned with the bourgeois culture they 
believed caused the war 
the journal published soupaults poem westwego and other 
works but he eventually fell out with breton and the surrealist 
movement accusing it of having become politicized 
soupault continued to write poetry and novels including the 
negro he turned to journalism in the 1930s reporting for the 
petit parisien newspaper and founding radio tunis in 1938 
he married renee niemeyer in 1937 they had two daughters 
after world war ii soupault directed the overseas broadcasts of 
radio television francaise and continued to work in broadcasting 
into the 1970s 
he continued writing poetry including day and night song 
and without sentences brought together in the poems and 
poetry collection in 1973 his last published work was memoires 
of the forgotten in 1981 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
