<TEXT>
sir eric gairy the eccentric 
former prime minister deposed in a leftist coup 11 years ago is 
attempting a comeback in grenadas second general election since 
the usled invasion of 1983 
gairy who dominated the tiny caribbean islands politics for 
three decades before his ouster faces competition from three 
moderates and one leftist in what could be a close vote tuesday 
we are right down to the wire but it is not clear who is in 
the lead said michael minors president of the grenada chamber 
of commerce 
the election falls on the 11th anniversary of the leftist coup 
that ousted gairys authoritarian regime and brought the peoples 
revolutionary government of the late prime minister maurice bishop 
to power 
an ideological rift within bishops government led to his 
assassination along with 10 other people on oct 19 1983 six 
days later us troops accompanied by a small regional force 
invaded the island and ousted a marxist junta that had seized power 
herbert blaize a staunch us ally won the first election 
after the invasion in 1984 he died in december at the age of 71 
gairy 68 is nearly blind with glaucoma and had said that he 
would not contest the election unless a miracle improved his 
sight 
but at a recent news conference he declared that a source 
which is greater than i ordained that he lead grenada once again 
despite his failing sight he asserted that it was no coincidence 
the election was being held on the anniversary of his ouster 
no man on earth could have arranged this he said it had 
to be arranged cosmically by a divine force 
gairy who was grenadas first prime minister after independence 
from britain in 1974 has been dogged throughout his career by 
allegations of corruption and repression 
his interest in the occult has made him an occasional object of 
ridicule he was deposed on march 13 1979 while in new york 
trying to persuade the united nations to investigate flying saucers 
but gairy maintains strong support among farm workers he 
founded grenadas first trade union the urban poor and the 
elderly his followers call him uncle gairy and voters are 
largely divided between pro and antigairy forces rather than 
along party lines 
since the invasion the united states has pumped more than 110 
million into grenada a nation of 94000 people but a widely 
expected bonanza of foreign investment has never occurred the 
campaign however has focused more on personalities than economic 
issues 
the other main contenders for prime minister are all regarded as 
moderates they are prime minister ben jones 66 a former foreign 
minister appointed as blaizes replacement pending the election 
keith mitchell 44 a useducated statistician who was fired by 
blaize as public works minister in a personality and policy 
dispute and nicholas brathwaite 65 who led an interim government 
after the us invasion 
a fifth candidate dr terrence marryshow 37 a cubantrained 
doctor and leader of the leftist maurice bishop patriotic movement 
is considered to have virtually no chance of winning 
no voter opinion polls have been published but most grenadians 
expect a close election some believe no single party will win a 
majority of the 15 seats in the house of representatives grenadas 
parliament which could result in a coalition government 
