<TEXT>
doctors on monday claimed initial success for an 
operation in which a man whose foot was severed by a subway train 
had it grafted onto his forearm 
a team of 10 doctors headed by dr maurice mimoun of the hopital 
rothschild worked more than six hours thursday to save the 
40yearold accident victims leg and foot 
the patient who was not identified fell onto the subway tracks 
just as the train was pulling into the station the wheels mangled 
his lower right leg and cleanly cut off the foot 
paramedics arrived within minutes and stabilized the victim who 
was bleeding heavily and going into shock other rescue workers 
found the severed foot on the track and whisked it to the hospital 
along with the man 
there i was confronted with a foot in perfect condition and a 
stump that needed several weeks to heal before the foot could be 
sewn back on mimoun said 
i had to think of a way to preserve the foot for as long as 
possible he said in an interview but i had never thought of 
doing this before 
if the legs heals properly it could take as little as three 
weeks or as long as three months mimoun said he will reattach the 
foot to the stump 
the patient should be able to walk normally without the 
temporary graft amputation would have been necessary he said 
the leg may be a little bit shorter he added but there are many 
ways to compensate and prevent a significant limp 
mimoun said the patient was under sedation and did not know he 
had undergone the surgery which was authorized by the victims 
family 
the results of the surgery were shown on french tv sunday night 
the swollen bloodstained foot resting in a prayer position over 
the hand which was uninjured 
mimoun said the use of relay grafts is common practice among 
plastic surgeons who often try to save healthy muscle or skin 
tissue by grafting it onto the forearm 
the forearm is used because it has two major blood vessels 
one of which can be used to vascularize whatever needs to be 
saved mimoun said he said the arm would supply the grafted foot 
with enough blood to keep it alive 
mimoun said the relay graft was a success thus far and gave the 
credit to being able to assemble a trauma team in 15 minutes he 
said some of the patients swelling had already gone down and there 
was no sign of infection 
its still too early to cry victory but im optimistic 
mimoun said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

