<TEXT>
the 1990 michelin guide book on monday awarded 
three stars to alain ducasse chef at the louis xv restaurant in 
montecarlos hotel de paris making him the youngest person ever 
to be so honored 
but the gourmets bible demoted loustau de baumaniere a famous 
restaurant in les baux in southern france to two stars after 35 
years as a threestar restaurant 
michelins famous red guide which goes on sale wednesday thus 
retained only 19 restaurants in the threestar category the 
bestselling guidebook which last year sold more than 750000 
copies can make or break a restaurants reputation 
ducasse 33 was jubilant at his three stars 
i think michelin is now starting to honor the younger 
generation as the hope of french cuisine he said in an interview 
the son of a farmer in southwest france ducasse said i grew 
up with the gardengrown vegetables with rabbits and chickens and 
my golden rule is to use the best of fresh ingredients 
ducasse learned his trade with several giants of french 
gastronomy starting at age 16 as an apprentice at the pavillon 
landais in soustons in southwestern france 
he then moved on to apprentice with michel guerard assisting in 
writing the famous lowfat cookbook cuisine minceur while at 
guerards threestar restaurant in eugenielesbains 
he also worked with such gastronomic luminaries as gaston 
lenotre in his pastry factory outside paris roger verge at his 
threestar moulin de mougins near cannes and alain chapel in 
mionnay near lyons 
in 1979 he returned to mougins as chef for verges less 
expensive annex lamandier and from 198186 was chef at the juana 
hotel in juanlespins 
in 1987 he was chosen personally by prince rainier of monaco as 
chef for the renovated belle epoquestyle louis xv restaurant at 
the hotel de paris 
the prince wanted this to be a worldclass restaurant 
ducasse said the louis xv is the only hotel restaurant to garner 
three stars in the history of the guide which started in 1900 
michelin also awarded a first star to the hotels rooftop grill 
room 
under ducasse the louis xv won its first star in 1987 and its 
second in 1988 before the 1990 accolade that made it worth a 
detour in the guidebooks parlance 
this is a spectacular rise as the guidebook is circumspect in 
its choices anonymous inspectors visit a restaurant several times 
for months or years before handing out the little stars that 
actually look like rosettes 
six restaurants were demoted from two stars to one including 
paris precatalan in the bois de boulogne and le petit bedon and 
57 restaurants fell from one star to none these include some 
wellknown paris eateries such as lamazere gildo le bistrot de 
paris and laquitaine 
the reason that baumaniere lost its third star is mainly that 
its going through a transitional period according to alain 
arnaud a spokesman for michelin arnaud said the former chef 
raymond thuilier has handed over the reins to his grandson and 
for michelin the results are still tentative 
meanwhile ducasse was busy in the monegasque kitchens turning 
out his famous delicacies that include a risotto with white italian 
truffles little vegetables sauteed with fresh black truffles 
warm seafood salad and giant pasta made with parsley to look like 
a mosaic 
of course im near italy and their cuisine influences me 
said ducasse im aiming to produce flavors of the sun in my 
food a mediterranean style based on its wonderful seafood 
vegetables olive oil 
just back from a tour of japan where he created a new menu for 
the okura hotel restaurant in tokyo ducasse said he was impressed 
by the freshness of japanese cuisine 
americans too have marvelous produce he said but the 
average american seems to consume too much sugar and starch making 
for less healthy and more fattening cuisine than japanese 
although the red guide will be snapped up for its restaurant 
recommendations it is still basically a guide for drivers giving 
exhaustive information about hotels distances between towns 
garages and auto dealers 
