military personnel who helped finance the 
construction of bases now slated for closing will be losing the 
400 million they invested in commissaries and base exchanges two 
congressmen said monday 
in effect military people paid 5 percent higher prices to 
finance construction of facilities such as pxs commissaries and 
recreation buildings rep marvin leath dtexas said in a 
statement they donated these facilities to the governments 
inventory upon completion 
joining leath in the criticism was rep david ob martin rny 
the commission on base realignment and closure recommended in 
december 1988 closing 86 domestic bases partly closing five others 
and changing the mission of 54 other installations for an estimated 
savings of 694 million a year and a 20year savings estimated at 
56 billion 
former defense secretary frank c carlucci approved the 
recommendations and congress despite some complaints last year 
overwhelmingly supported the commissions decision 
earlier this year defense secretary dick cheney recommended 
closing or scaling back more than 72 domestic facilities and 14 
overseas installations members of congress including rep les 
aspin dwis chairman of the house armed services committee have 
criticized cheneys list as partisan 
leath and martin said that based on their calculations closing 
the 86 bases as well as the domestic installations cheney has 
recommended would cost us personnel about 240 million if 
overseas bases were included the cost would be approximately 400 
million 
base closures are being billed as a step to reduce costs to 
the taxpayer martin said in a statement military personnel 
are taxpayers too they had to dig deep into their pockets to build 
these facilities and they should be compensated for their 
contributions 
martin gave no specific proposals on how the personnel might be 
compensated 
leath is the chairman and martin the ranking republican on the 
house armed services panel on morale welfare and recreation 
