<TEXT>
us subsidies on wheat sold to the soviet 
union were worth 481 million over 29 months the general 
accounting office reported 
the soviet union got the benefit of lower prices from the 
largest amount that the us government spent on shipments to any 
one country the subsidies are collected by us exporting 
companies which then ship to foreign buyers at less than market 
prices 
the object is to help sell us farm products in competition 
with subsidies by governments of other producer countries trying to 
help their own farmers the program is aimed especially at 
competition from the 12 countries of the european economic 
community where france and west germany are big exporters of wheat 
wheat is the major item under what the federal government calls 
its export enhancement program but subsidies are also paid on a 
variety of products from eggs to milk cows 
detailed figures in the report made available recently cover 
oct 1 1986 through feb 28 1989 during that period the total 
subsidies to all exporters amounted to 23 billion total sales of 
us products helped by the subsidies were 68 billion of which 
55 billion was for sales of wheat 
five countries were the biggest wheat buyers under the program 
the soviet union china algeria egypt and morocco 
critics say the subsidized sales discourage those governments 
from paying better prices to their own farmers and that the bread 
from the wheat is so cheap that some feed it to animals 
the agriculture department put the total cost of the subsidies 
up to last week at 27 billion since the program began in 1985 it 
said later detailed figures for the soviet union and other 
individual countries were confidential 
its largely a passthrough operation to help us farmers 
said rob johnson vice president for public affairs of cargill inc 
our commissions have averaged less than onehalf of one percent 
of sales 
cargill one of the worlds biggest grain dealers collected the 
largest amount in subsidies 4449 million 
how much of that was profit is impossible to estimate said 
allen i mendelowitz director of international trade and finance 
issues at the gao his report was submitted to rep kika de la 
garza dtex chairman of the house agriculture commitee 
mendelowitz said cargills earnings come not only from 
commissions but also depend on the prices it paid us farmers 
which may have been higher than the prices it received in moscow 
as well as on the subsidies it received from the us government 
those subsidies are paid in the form of surplus farm products 
already owned by the government 
egypt was the second biggest beneficiary under the us program 
which paid us dealers 3118 million in such commodities to help 
exports there egypt got frozen poultry dairy cattle and semolina 
too but wheat and wheat flour were much the biggest items 
china received some cattle but mostly wheat subsidies for 
shipments there totaled 2995 million 
algeria a major wheat producer also got mainly wheat from the 
united states the bonuses on exports there were worth 2069 
million including some for barley semolina and vegetable oil 
the gao is congress watchdog agency on government spending 
