<TEXT>
arab nomads and tribal farmers clashed in 
western sudan in the latest outbreak of an ancient feud killing 69 
people and burning down 14 villages the official news agency 
reported monday 
the fighting between the arabs and the fur a moslem nonarab 
farming tribe took place last week at the shattaya villages of 
wadi salih in the darfour region the sudan news agency said 
without giving a specific cause for the latest unrest 
it said the governor of darfour maj gen abulgasim ibrahim 
toured the area to try to reconcile the two sides reporting from 
elfasher the capital of darfour the agency said the governor has 
ordered weapons collected from the fighters 
it said he also appealed to both sides to abide by a july 
reconciliation agreement the accord stipulated that each tribe pay 
the other compensation for losses in previous clashes 
western relief workers say the ageold clashes escalated last 
year they say 2000 to 3000 people were killed in the darfour 
clashes 
every winter for hundreds of years cattleherding baggara and 
other smaller nomadic tribes have interloped on fur farms as they 
trekked toward water and grazing lands to the south 
they fought brief battles with limited deaths differences were 
resolved in traditional peace councils after the fighting blood 
money was paid for victims and compensation for destroyed farms 
