<TEXT>
the vow of celibacy taken by roman catholic 
priests and nuns was one reason they were sought as potential 
subjects for an experimental aids vaccine developed by dr jonas 
salk a researcher said monday 
the researcher katharine munson also said it was archbishop 
roger mahonys idea to suggest an age of 65 or older in a jan 25 
letter to 3500 priests and nuns telling them that volunteers were 
needed 
mahony however denied sunday that anyone suggested to him that 
catholic clergy were being sought because of their celibate lives 
youre really looking for people who have a commitment to 
humankind and willingness to take risks to benefit others he 
said 
munson clinical director of the study at the university of 
southern californias norris cancer institute said the program was 
in no special need of candidates and has already been contacted by 
hundreds of people 
salk works at the la jolla calif institute that bears his 
name but the aids research is to be done at the norris clinic 
on monday the us food and drug administration approved 
expanded testing of the vaccine outside california 
reached at his home monday salk declined to comment on the 
study if i start giving interviews there will be no end to 
it said the 75yearold physician who in the 1950s created the 
first polio vaccine pronounced safe and effective 
munson said the vaccine salk hiv immunogen is being 
administered to 90 volunteers who have already tested positive for 
the virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome 
in the next phase of testing 10 volunteers without the virus 
will be given the vaccine munson said she didnt know whether any 
of those being interviewed were roman catholic clergy 
the prototype salk vaccine is the only one among several being 
developed from the whole aids virus critics say that if live 
strains of the virus contaminate the vaccine volunteers could be 
accidentally infected 
researchers are trying to find out whether the inactivated virus 
used in the vaccine will cause the body to produce specific cells 
called t cells that destroy other cells infected with the virus 
munson said priests and nuns were sought as volunteers because 
in groups of people who have taken a vow of celibacy there are 
likely to be fewer people who get involved in sexual activity 
one of the ways aids is transmitted 
in this way researchers could be certain that if the test 
subjects developed the disease it would have been caused by a 
faulty vaccine she said 
munson agreed the appeal was also to priests and nuns who live 
an altruistic lifestyle and help aids patients 
it wasnt our decision to ask for people who are 65 said 
munson the archbishop put that in the letter if it the 
vaccine is ineffective someone might want to be older rather than 
young 
the age is not our standard each person young or old will 
be screened she said 
mahony said dr brian e henderson director of norris told him 
at their last meeting a few weeks ago that about six nuns had 
contacted the doctor as well as one or two priests 
the study is being conducted under a california law that permits 
such experiments without fda approval as long as all the materials 
are made in california 
munson said the second phase of the test injecting people who 
have tested negative for the virus awaits state approval salk 
said he will inject himself with the drug when testing is approved 
volunteer candidates had been calling regularly at the rate of 
five to 15 a day munson said adding that more calls were coming 
following the publicity the program received over the weekend 
while roman catholic officials insisted there was nothing more 
to mahonys letter than passing on information on behalf of 
henderson some medical ethicists wondered whether church politics 
was behind the move 
the roman catholic church has come under a lot of criticism 
from the aids community who have called it an obstacle to 
education an obstacle to the distribution of contraceptives 
said arthur caplan a medical ethicist at the university of 
minnesota 
to see the church participating in a vaccine trial carries 
with it a political as well as an ethical message he said 
there are many dangerous diseases for which there are such 
programs i dont think its an accident that this letter went out 
about aids 
