<DOCNO> AP900312-0155 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal regulators should think about moving 
stock trading off exchange floors to computer screens a report to 
congress said monday the regulators said they werent convinced 
the general accounting office the auditing and investigative 
agency of congress said the securities and exchange commission 
should consider a proposal to repeal a new york stock exchange rule 
requiring trades of most listed stocks to be executed on the 
exchange floor 
a rule that forbids afterhours trading of listed stocks which 
tends to push afterhours trading to foreign exchanges also should 
be reviewed the report said 
trading rules were eased in 1979 to permit offfloor trading of 
newly listed stocks but a decade later most stocks still were 
initially listed before 1979 trades of 89 of the new york stock 
exchanges 100 most active shares still must be routed through the 
exchange floor 
the gao noting the rapid evolution of computer and 
communications technology said it is time for the commission to 
reconsider rules banning most offfloor trading 
the commission disagreed saying its 1979 study of offfloor 
trading was complex and that it would not dismantle the floor 
system until market participants determine a new system would be 
better than the old 
on the new york stock exchange the nations principal exchange 
brokers bring orders to a specific spot on the floor designated for 
trading in the stock they are buying or selling 
there they must deal by open outcry with other floor 
brokers if there are any if there are none others the broker 
seeking to trade may deal with a specialist another broker 
charged by the exchange with standing ready to buy or sell at all 
times 
critics contend that the use of trading floors and specialists 
restricts price competition 
supporters of the current system however argue that a central 
location for trading preserves the benefits of an auction market 
in trading by computer a broker lists bids or offerings on a 
screen for others to accept or reject changing prices as he or she 
sees fit 
the sec agreed that a review of afterhours trading was in order 
even though in 1986 the commission rejected a recommendation from 
its staff that the agency ask the new york stock exchange to 
consider it 
as a result exchange member brokers and dealers who wish 
to trade exchangelisted stocks when us markets are closed must 
do so in foreign markets the gao said 
the report dated monday was delivered to the senate banking 
committee and the house energy and commerce committee 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

