a summary of developments in the news industry for the week of 
march 512 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
newspapers need to offer more services to 
compete for readers who move from town to town without developing 
ties to their communities the chairman of the knightridder 
newspaper group said march 7 
transiency is bad for the country and its also terrible for 
newspapers said james batten who also serves as knightridders 
chief executive officer 
batten was executive in residence for wichita state universitys 
center for entrepreneurship 
he said one of the biggest challenges that newspapers must 
confront is that readers have or think they have less time to 
read than in the past 
people are feeling the stress of time poverty its tough to 
wedge in everything we may want to do he said 
adults who say they read a newspaper every day dropped from 73 
percent in 1967 to 51 percent last year batten said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
americans are becoming more apathetic 
about their communities and their governments while people in 
eastern europe are struggling to attain many of the freedoms we 
take for granted an executive of a dallas newspaper said march 5 
we have a chance if we dont blow it to help reinvent 
freedom burl osborne president and editor of the dallas morning 
news told a group at kentucky wesleyan college 
we have great power to persuade we can set the public 
agenda said osborne 
in south africa where nelson mandela now walks free the wall 
of apartheid has begun to crumble he said we need to rekindle 
the passion for our own freedoms in ourselves in our newspapers 
and in our communities 
for example newspapers should tell readers how to get involved 
in their community osborne said newspapers also must tell readers 
how problems around the world can affect them locally 
we need to do a better job than weve done explaining that 
acid rain over canada means something in kentucky he said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the government of china denounced a us embassy 
investigation into the treatment of american journalists denying 
charges that its security forces have stepped up surveillance of 
foreign reporters 
correspondents from nearly a dozen foreign news organizations 
say they have been followed or their chinese sources harassed by 
plainclothes police in recent weeks 
foreign ministry spokesman li zhaoxing said march 8 that such 
reports were groundless and that reporters who carry out normal and 
legitimate news coverage need not worry that they might run into 
troubles 
an investigation into the claims ordered by the state department 
was an interference in chinas internal affairs li said 
should an investigation be really necessary the 
justiceupholding people in the world would have every reason to 
ask how many things has this superpower done in broad daylight 
over the years to trample upon the sovereignty and infringe upon 
the human rights of other nations 
the surveillance of foreign reporters appeared to step up after 
martial law was lifted in beijing on jan 11 with some journalists 
saying they have been tailed even while jogging or shopping 
journalists say chinese security agents have also tried to 
photograph their meetings with chinese sources and have 
interrogated their chinese contacts 
</TEXT>
