the donald and ivana saga may stir the hearts 
of reporters and editors but most americans have heard enough of 
the trumps according to a nationwide survey of news interests 
released march 8 
the monthly times mirror news interest index showed a record 55 
percent of the 1226 people surveyed thought there was too much 
news about the trumps domestic battle it was by far the largest 
overcovered rating ever accorded a story since the poll was 
begun in 1986 
the survey conducted by the gallup organization found no 
single news story dominated public attention in the last month the 
freeing of black south african leader nelson mandela and political 
changes in the soviet union led the index with very closely 
followed ratings of 30 percent and 28 percent respectively 
the index is sponsored by the times mirror center for the people 
amp the press based on the total sample of 1226 adults the poll 
has a 95 percent chance of being within 3 percentage points of the 
results that would be obtained if the entire adult population were 
interviewed 
