<TEXT>
john neville the comic british butler on 
nbcs grand doesnt apologize for forsaking the shakespearean 
stage for a hollywood sitcom 
its not the first time that neville has given his career an 
unusual twist nor is it the first time hes been taken to task for 
it 
he was a matinee idol on the london stage and an heir to the 
crown of laurence olivier when he abruptly moved to canada in the 
early 1970s last year he resigned as artistic director of the 
stratford festival in canada 
i know what people are saying neville said in an interview 
shortly before returning to london to star in school for 
scandal at the national theater he first starred in the play at 
the haymarket theater in 1962 
they never say it to your face they say well hes sold out 
and gone to hollywood i say well im going back to the 
national theater in london 
desmond the redoubtable butler he plays in grand probably 
would offer a more cheeky response desmond trades quip for quip 
with his cranky master once bedded one of the bosss wives and for 
a time feared he was the real father of the bosss son 
the comedy whose quirky plot twists and unpredictable 
characters are reminiscent of soap made its debut in january 
its time slot after the cosby show and cheers on thursday 
have so far given it a charmed life 
this is work ive never done before neville says ive 
done virtually everything else i was attracted to the quality of 
grand it gives me a lot of pleasure ive never in my career 
experienced a fiveday week which at my age is rather pleasurable 
especially in california 
neville and his wife have an apartment here but have kept their 
home in stratford five of their children live in canada and one 
lives in england he would like to do more film work in 1988 he 
played the title role in the movie the adventures of baron 
munchausen 
he had resigned as head of the stratford festival before he was 
offered the role in grand 
i had no idea what i was going to do next he says thats 
been the story of my life ive run theaters for 25 years ive 
always given notice early having no idea what i would do each 
time something has always come up 
what attracted me was the quality of the writing the show was 
created by michael leeson who wrote taxi and the movie the war 
of the roses id never done a sitcom before 
grand follows the lives of eight people in a small 
pennsylvania town thats difficult to do its unusual for a 
sitcom because it has a kind of serial feel one show follows 
another you get to know the characters but it may take some time 
to find an audience people remind me that it took hill street 
blues two years to find an audience 
neville did very little television in canada although he had 
done quite a lot in england he starred as the duke of marlboro 
one of britains greatest generals and an ancestor of winston 
churchill in the bbc miniseries the first churchill it was 
the series that launched pbss masterpiece theatre in 1971 
he was at the old vic where he did nothing but shakespeare for 
six years he became a matinee idol in alfie then quit to 
become artistic director of the nottingham playhouse he was 
awarded the order of the british empire in 1965 
neville admits it was a major disappointment when he wasnt even 
approached about the movie role of alfie given to michael caine 
in 1966 
in 1972 he abruptly quit england for canada i had been asked 
to ottawa to direct the rivals for four weeks he says i had 
a very successful and illustrious career in england but i never 
went back i fell in love with canada i moved my wife and children 
there my wife wasnt surprised because ive always done kind of 
wayward and unexpected things in my career 
ive had no regrets about the moves ive made i consider 
myself a north american england isnt what it was when i grew up 
prior to grand neville completed four years at the 
stratford shakespearean festival a threetheater complex with a 
total of 3800 seats 
thats a lot of seats to fill he says people came from 
all over ontario from chicago ohio and even california we did 12 
to 13 plays a year with three plays running at once its 
predominantly shakespeare but we did cat on a hot tin roof last 
year 
we had a 45 million debt when i took over thats a lot for 
a theater i paid off the debt and left a healthy profit im very 
good at that i should run a movie studio 
</TEXT>
