<TEXT>
for some people a chorus line was more than 
a musical it was a way of life 
alyce gilbert has worked on broadways longestrunning show 
since the beginning from its first preview performances at the new 
york shakespeare festival public theater in april 1975 to its 
opening at broadways shubert theater the following july and 
throughout its 15year run 
now her job and those of its 58 other production people 26 
musicians and 34 dancers will end march 31 when a chorus line 
closes after 6104 performances 
gilbert is the musicals wardrobe mistress a quaint title for 
someone who must deal with four loads of dirty laundry every 
workday and twice on matinee days thats not to mention her 
finding getting repaired and keeping track of shoes socks 
buttons glass beads leotards pants jump suits jackets and top 
hats during what usually is a 12hour day or longer 
wardrobe is about continuity says the woman who first 
looked after costumes at age 12 for a childrens theater company in 
her hometown of milwaukee its not design its about things 
staying the same or kept within a certain parameter 
gilbert has the responsibility of maintaining the shows 
costumes designed by threetime tony winner theoni v aldredge she 
has had to make the replacement clothes look the way aldredge 
intended them to look a decade and a half ago that can mean a lot 
of problems 
youre dealing with some things that are rather firmly rooted 
in the fashion of 1975 that dont exist anymore gilbert says 
for one thing dance clothes have changed when a chorus 
line first opened dancewear mostly was nylon helanca now its 
milliskin made out of lycra a shiny spandex fiber that prevails 
everything in the world is made out of that now gilbert 
says so the musicals nylon dance clothes have to be specially 
ordered and then all the dancewear except for the womens black 
leotards has to be dyed 
theonis colors are very specific gilbert says all the 
women in the show wear some kind of red from pink to lavender to 
burgundy to maroon the men are dressed in blues browns and greens 
we took the bellbottoms out of the pants in 1981 it took a 
long time before they went out of dance pants primarily because it 
makes your legs look longer and thats something dancers always 
love 
gilbert has witnessed not only a revolution in dancewear but a 
change in the shapes of the dancers themselves 
it used to be a very long thin chorus line she says 
over the 15 years its become a much more athletic body dancers 
go to gyms they pump they do very distinct things to build bulky 
muscles which you never saw in 1975 it was not aesthetically 
pleasing then but somewhere along the line the publics eye 
changed and so did the choreographers 
gilberts workday usually has begun at 10 am in the basement 
of the shubert in a catacomblike space crammed with racks and 
boxes of costumes in every size and color 
its the buyitwhenyouseeitandkeepit syndrome she 
laughs weve got a lot of weird stuff around 
here she starts the days first load of laundry the dancewear 
is washed after each performance in a coldwater detergent the 
glittery finale costumes are pressed and checked for broken beads 
different dressers the show has five have beadin calls to 
go over the finale costumes to replace beads 
that costume has become a symbol of what broadway is 
gilbert says director michael bennett originally asked aldredge 
for red finale clothes similar to what he had used in follies 
but she came up with her own unique design 
it is based on everything being reflected gilbert says 
everything shines the fabrics the shoes the mens are patent 
leather the womens are satin the beads are glass when the light 
hits those clothes they look gold they look silver they look 
white its amazing what vanishes from them in terms of wear 
during the day gilbert deals with whatever has to be replaced 
or repaired toward evening the stage manager wanders by and 
announces who will be on stage that night a chorus line is a 
show in which understudies get a chance to perform frequently that 
means hauling out finale costumes for the replacement dancers 
about a half hour before curtain the five dressers come in the 
dancewear has been separated onto hangers one costume to a hanger 
and sent to the dressing rooms 
while the musical starts the finale costumes are set on racks 
at the side of the stage for the evenings splashy closing number 
during the show gilbert and the dressers fuss with the costume 
worn by cassie the lead female dancer and then get ready for the 
finale when the dressers go to help with the dancers finale 
changes gilbert goes too she personally hands out the top hats 
to them 
youre dealing with 17 people and 17 hats that look the 
same she says we dont keep the hats with finale costumes 
because its dark its easy to come up with the wrong hat if 
youre not focusing on that 
the process is repeated eight times a week 
youre in a rather unique position doing wardrobe 
particularly in this show says gilbert who got her start in 
1968 doing shows offbroadway ive learned that dancers are 
really so gallant they can be silly they can be petty they can 
be lots of things but when they have to go out and dance theres 
an extraordinary bravery 
all dance ever really gives them is the chance to be able to 
do it anything else is extra 
gilbert took two 6month leaves from a chorus line over the 
years to work on two other bennett shows ballroom and 
dreamgirls she always came back 
when a chorus line closes shell move over to grand 
hotel the tommy tune musical that has lavish 1920sstyle 
costumes and then there will probably be other shows she adds 
wistfully 
</TEXT>
