<DOCNO> AP900312-0245 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
atampt signed an agreement monday to share a key 
ingredient used to make advanced semiconductors under the auspices 
of sematech the consortium of computer chip makers formed to boost 
us semiconductor competitiveness 
under the agreement american telephone amp telegraph co will 
allow a division of olin corp to make and sell a chemical used to 
etch extremely detailed electronic circuitry on chips 
the chemical called deep uv resist allows chip designers 
to pack a greater number of circuits on chips than current 
technologies 
in making chips circuitry is etched on silicon wafers using a 
lightsensitive chemical or resist and a mask whose function 
is similar to that of a negative in photography 
atampt bell laboratories has invented a version of the chemical 
that is used with ultraviolet light instead of the visible light 
currently used 
however olin will not be the first company to market 
ultravioletbased resist shipley co inc of newton mass has 
been selling ultraviolet resist for several years and it is being 
used by chip makers to test the new technology said eric alling a 
marketing manager for the company 
were very encouraged atampt has elected to expand the viabilty 
of deep uv technology alling said 
the uv resist can produce highly complex computer chips with 
circuits as thin as 03 micrometers or about 400 times smaller 
than a human hair atampt said 
such dimensions are essential for packing more processing 
power speed and memory into the chips of the future said arno 
penzias vice president of research for bell labs 
circuitry on most chips today is 1 to 12 microns wide while it 
reaches 08 microns in more advanced chips 
atampt said it also is working on two other advanced technologies 
for making even more complex computer chips xray lithography and 
electronbeam techniques 
japanese chip makers are believed to be concentrating on 
ultraviolet lithography as the next generation of technology while 
also studying the xray technique european makers are actively 
exploring xrays industry analysts said 
perhaps what this may indicate is that the use of xray 
techniques may be further down the road than the japanese 
thought analyst jay ritter of duff amp phelps inc in chicago said 
of the atampt pact 
adopting either technique would require an enormous investment 
in new chip manufacturing equipment but the xray technology would 
be more costly than the ultraviolet technique said mark 
fitzgerald an analyst with dataquest inc of san jose calif the 
research firm believes ultraviolet etching will be used for the 
next generation of semiconductors 
sematech officials hailed the atampt agreement 
the deep uv resist is the future in semiconductor 
manufacturing and will produce semiconductors that compete in the 
global market in terms of performance and price said robert 
noyce president and chief executive of the consortium 
sematech was founded by 14 us semiconductor manufacturers 
including atampt under the sponsorship of the us government which 
splits the cost of the consortium with the companies 
</TEXT>
