<TEXT>
a former food lion employee filed a 
federal class action lawsuit against the fastgrowing supermarket 
chain monday alleging the company has illegally denied workers 
retirement and health benefits 
company officials said the benefit plans are administered 
according to law and called the suit an attempt by the united food 
and commercial workers union to pressure the company into 
recognizing the union the company is nonunion 
the union has a history of creating these lawsuits and the 
most mileage they get out of it is in media coverage that they have 
filed it said food lion inc spokesman mike mozingo in a 
telephone interview from the companys salisbury nc 
headquarters 
food lion has 675 stores in 10 states from delaware to florida 
including 81 in south carolina 
the lawsuit filed by former employee rickey bryant of west 
columbia alleges the company used a scheme to terminate employees 
to prevent them from receiving full or partial profitsharing 
benefits a program which serves as the companys retirement plan 
in addition it alleges employees are unlawfully discharged on 
the grounds of gross misconduct so the company does not have to 
continue providing health benefits for employees and their families 
the suit said those who have the most to gain when a nonvested 
worker leaves and forfeits profit sharing are the longestserving 
and highestpaid employees of the company 
the suit filed in us district court in charleston claims 
bryants termination in 1988 after nine years with the company was 
a pretext to deny him 55 percent of the approximately 67000 he 
had in profit sharing 
as of december 1987 the profitsharing plan had 20907 active 
participants and 192 million in assets but only 81 people were 
fully vested and only 2956 were partially vested the suit said 
because of the high turnover rate at food lion there are many 
thousands of employees who are or have been participants in the 
plan and who will derive no benefit the suit charges 
among the damages the lawsuit is seeking from food lion are 
bryants reinstatement and restoration of back pay and lost health 
and profitsharing plan for bryant and other defendants 
nicholas clark the assistant general counsel for the united 
food and commercial workers international who drafted the lawsuit 
said the union came to bryants aid even though food lion is a 
nonunion company 
he said the class action lawsuit could potentially involve 
thousands of former employees and millions of dollars in benefits 
the suit has much more significance than just food lion 
clark added he said it could affect any employer with a high 
turnover and who structures profit sharing so workers do not get 
their benefits 
mozingo said he could not comment on the specifics of the 
complaint because he had not seen a copy of the lawsuit 
more than 21000 of the chains 42000 employees are fully or 
partially vested in the profit sharing plan ten years ago the 
chain which is opening over 100 stores annually employed only 
4849 workers 
a lot of people working for food lion have not been here that 
long because we simply didnt have that many stores open mozingo 
said 
he said the union has tried unsuccessfully to organize the chain 
and they have not been able to get to first base with our 
employees 
they look at our 40000 employees and see these people arent 
sending in dues every month mozingo said they look to 
discredit the company and stop our growth 
</TEXT>
