<TEXT>
the ohio supreme court on monday granted a 
delay in arguments in the states appeal from two criminal 
convictions stemming from the collapse of home state savings bank 
the court said oral arguments involving former home state owner 
marvin warner and a former president of the thrift david schiebel 
will be rescheduled no later than june 6 if the state and the 
defendants lawyers meet a prehearing briefing schedule 
arguments had been scheduled for march 27 but special 
prosecutor lawrence kane jr of cincinnati is requesting the delay 
pending disposition of some other matters in the case attorney 
general anthony j celebrezze jr said 
cincinnatibased home state collapsed on march 8 1985 four 
days after esm government securities inc of fort lauderdale fla 
was declared insolvent home state lost 144 million through its 
securities transactions with esm 
the failure of home state led to ohios savings and loan 
industry crisis of that year 
warner schiebel and another former home state president burton 
bongard were convicted on march 2 1987 of state charges related 
to home states collapse 
warner was convicted of nine felonies six counts of 
misapplying about 14 million in bank money through unauthorized 
payments to esm and three counts of securities violations he was 
acquitted of 76 other counts 
schiebel was found guilty of three securities violations and 
bongard was convicted of 82 counts of misapplication and 
unauthorized transfer of funds 
warner had been sentenced to 3 years in prison and fined 22 
million and schiebel was sentenced to six months both are free on 
bond pending their appeals 
bongard later pleaded guilty to loan violations and received a 
4year prison sentence he was released from prison in july 1989 
on probation 
a threejudge panel of the 1st ohio district court of appeals in 
cincinnati overturned the convictions of warner and schiebel on 
nov 15 1989 
last week celebrezze defended the costs of the special 
prosecutor about 59 million so far by saying he helped the 
state recover 135 million it spent to protect depositors and 
stablize the ohio thrift industry in the wake of home states 
collaspe 
