<TEXT>
ibm on monday introduced a computer system for 
banks that caputures electronic images of checks and electronically 
reads and records their amount 
the system should greatly reduce the amount of time and money 
spent by banks in manually entering into computers the amount of 
checks and in storing and collating the checks international 
business machines corp said 
ibm also said banks could improve customer service by providing 
images of actual checks along with their customers monthly 
statements 
the system developed in cooperation with six major banks 
employs imaging scanners that can take an electronic picture of 
checks at up to 2400 checks per minute 
the system employs compression technology that reduces the 
amount of data that must be stored to capture an image of a check 
or other document compression technology is needed to allow 
existing computer equipment to handle the vast amount of data 
needed to store an image as opposed to storing data such as 
figures 
the equipment can electronically read the amount of money a 
check is written for either hand printed or typewritten in 
about half the cases ibm said when the equipment is unsure of a 
figure it will display an image of the check on a screen for a 
bank employee to verify the figure or manually enter it into the 
computer 
ibms main competitor in the bank check imaging market is unisys 
corp said nick allen an analyst with gartner group inc a 
consulting firm in stamford conn 
he said the market for the equipment should be promising as 
banks work to limit the labor involved in processing checks 
weve only recently reached the processing power capability to 
do this kind of thing he said 
check processing of banks already is a major market for ibm 
he added what this does is stimulate demand for hardware 
</TEXT>
