<TEXT>
federal regulators should give new thought to 
sweeping changes in us stock markets including moving trading 
from actionpacked exchange floors to flickering computer screens 
a congressional report said monday 
specifically the general accounting office congress auditing 
and investigative agency said the securities and exchange 
commission should consider a proposal to repeal a new york stock 
exchange rule requiring trades of most listed stocks to be executed 
on the exchange floor 
a rule that forbids afterhours trading of listed stocks in 
effect forcing such trading to foreign exchanges also should be 
reviewed the report said 
trading rules were eased in 1979 to permit offfloor trading of 
newly listed stocks but a decade later most stocks still were 
initially listed before 1979 trades of 89 of the new york stock 
exchanges 100 most active shares still must be routed through the 
exchange floor 
the gao noting the rapid evolution of computer and 
communications technology said it is time for the sec to 
reconsider rules banning most offfloor trading 
the sec disagreed saying its 1979 study of offfloor trading 
was complex and that it would not dismantle the floor system until 
market participants determine the resulting new system would be 
better than the old method 
critics contend that the current structure of the market 
including the use of trading floors and specialist brokers who 
make a market in the stock restricts price competition 
supporters of the current system however argue that a central 
location for trading preserves the benefits of an auction market 
the sec agreed that a review of afterhours trading was in order 
even though in 1986 the commission rejected a recommendation from 
it staff that the agency ask the new york stock exchange to 
consider permitting afterhours trading 
as a result exchange member brokers and dealers who wish 
to trade exchangelisted stocks when us markets are closed must 
do so in foreign markets the gao said 
the report dated monday was delivered to the senate banking 
committee and the house energy and commerce committee 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

