<TEXT>
atampt announced monday that all of its 
newly manufactured telephones and answering machines will be packed 
in 100 percent biodegradable material a move expected to reduce 
the companys distribution and waste disposal costs 
the new packaging which uses corrugated cardboard in place of 
bulkier foam to protect the companys line of small consumer 
products will make its packaged products about one quarter smaller 
than their predecessors said lee blitch atampts director of 
advertising and packaging 
he also said the packaging will disintegrate easily in landfills 
we will save on shipping and waste hauling costs because 
everything will be 25 to 30 percent smaller he said this is 
also welcome by retailers who will be able to stock more of the 
smaller products on their shelves 
the new packaging standards apply only to atampts line of small 
consumer products and will not affect such large items as personal 
computers office switchboard systems and other large components 
said atampt spokeswoman lynn newman 
last year the company announced it had eliminated all sources 
of chloroflourocarbons known as cfcs from its packaging 
materials cfcs contained in such materials as styrofoam and 
aerosol propellants are blamed for the deterioration of the 
earths protective ozone layer 
the new yorkbased company which reported 361 billion in 
revenues for 1989 maintains a team of environmental engineers who 
work with its bell laboratories subsidiary to improve packaging 
techniques eliminate hazardous materials and encourage recycling 
ms newman said 
the changes were made she said because the old foam inserts 
that protected cordless and corded telephones and answering 
machines were difficult to collapse and did not disintegrate in 
landfills 
she said information on specific cost savings expected would not 
be released because the company did not want to give competitors 
any hint of the sales performance of their telephone and answering 
machine lines 
